<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About Whirlpool dryer repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Whirlpool is the highest-volume dryer brand on our service mix, and F01 is the code we see most often.</h2>

    <p>Whirlpool Corporation is the largest major-appliance manufacturer in the world, headquartered in Benton Harbor, Michigan, with significant US dryer manufacturing. Across our five-county SoCal service area, Whirlpool dryers outnumber every other brand combined, production-builder homes from 2010-2022 across the Inland Empire are dominated by Whirlpool laundry, and Cabrio + Duet companion units appear constantly in West LA renovation kitchens. Maytag and Kenmore-branded dryers built on the same Whirlpool chassis add to the platform's footprint; service items cross-fit at the part-number level.</p>

    <p>One Whirlpool dryer service reality dominates how we approach diagnostic calls: the <strong>F01 error code</strong>. F01 indicates a main control board (CCU) internal fault, typically a relay failure or solder crack on a high-current connection. The well-documented root cause is a manufacturing pattern where insufficient solder on critical high-current points cracks and burns over time, often surfacing after a power surge or extended outage. About 15% of F01 codes clear with a 5-10 minute power cycle at no parts cost; the remaining 85% need CCU replacement ($345-$525 with labor). We always try the reset first.</p>

    <p>The second consistent theme: <strong>vent inspection on every no-heat call without exception</strong>. A blocked or restricted dryer vent is the root cause of about 70% of blown thermal fuses we encounter on Whirlpool dryers. The thermal fuse is a safety device, it blew because the dryer overheated, and replacing the fuse without clearing the vent guarantees a callback. We clear the vent at every no-heat repair as part of the diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 COMMON PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Common Whirlpool dryer problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we see fail most often on Whirlpool dryers, and how we diagnose each.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Whirlpool dryer service calls cluster around five symptom categories. Each has a predictable diagnostic tree we follow before quoting parts.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>F01 control panel error:</strong> Main control board (CCU) fault, Whirlpool's signature dryer issue. Try a 5-10 minute power cycle reset first (clears about 15%); if F01 returns, CCU replacement runs $345-$525.</li>
      <li><strong>Runs but won't heat:</strong> Almost always a blown thermal fuse triggered by a clogged or restricted vent (70% of cases) or an open heating element (year 8-12 wear). Vent inspection on every call without exception. Thermal fuse + vent clear $145-$245; heating element $285-$425.</li>
      <li><strong>Squealing or grinding noise:</strong> Drum belt fatigue and idler pulley wear, typical year 6-9. Replaced as a kit ($195-$295) since both wear together. Sometimes the drum support rollers also need replacement on units 10+ years old.</li>
      <li><strong>Won't start at all:</strong> Door switch failure (most common, $125-$185) or, less often, drive motor or thermal cut-off fuse. The door switch is a small part that triggers the start sequence, when it fails, the dryer is electrically dead even if the controls light up.</li>
      <li><strong>Takes multiple cycles to dry:</strong> Vent restriction or weak heating element. We test airflow at the exterior vent (should produce 700+ CFM) and ohm-test the heating element. On Whirlpool dryers, "two-cycle drying" is almost always a vent issue first, an element issue second.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Whirlpool's smart-dryer features (SmartDispense, Wi-Fi controls, app integration on premium models) generally don't fail in isolation, when "the app says my dryer is broken," the underlying fault is almost always one of the five categories above, surfaced through the app rather than caused by it.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 F01 DEEP-DIVE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, F01 error troubleshooting</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The Whirlpool F01 code, what it means, how we fix it.</h2>

    <p>F01 is the error code we see most often on Whirlpool Cabrio, Duet, Duet Sport, and standard WED/WGD dryers, including the Kenmore and Maytag-branded units built on the same Whirlpool platform. The code indicates a main control board (CCU) internal failure, typically a relay or high-current solder connection.</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">What's actually failing</h3>
    <p>The CCU is a small printed circuit board mounted on the back of Duet dryers and inside the rear panel on Cabrio and standard top-load dryers. It controls all dryer functions, heating element, motor, sensors, panel display, and drum operations. The well-documented manufacturing issue is that the factory solder process leaves insufficient solder on certain high-current connections (particularly the heater relay terminals). Over years of thermal cycling, those undersolderd joints crack and burn. A power surge or extended outage often pushes a marginal connection over the edge, which is why customers frequently describe the F01 starting "after a thunderstorm" or "after our power was out."</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Diagnostic order on every F01 we see</h3>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Step 1, Reset.</strong> Unplug the dryer (or kill the breaker) for 5-10 minutes, then power back on. About <strong>15% of F01 codes clear at this step</strong> with no parts cost. We perform this step on the diagnostic visit before doing anything else.</li>
      <li><strong>Step 2, Confirm code returns.</strong> Run a short test cycle. If F01 returns within a cycle (or immediately), the CCU has confirmed failure.</li>
      <li><strong>Step 3, Verify part number.</strong> Duet, Cabrio, Duet Sport, and standard WED/WGD use different CCU part numbers even within the same generation. We pull the dryer's serial sticker and confirm the exact OEM Whirlpool part before ordering.</li>
      <li><strong>Step 4, CCU replacement.</strong> $345-$525 with labor. On Duet, the CCU is mounted on the back panel and accessible without major disassembly. On Cabrio and standard top-loaders, access is from the rear panel, slightly more involved but still a 1-2 hour repair.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Some online guides suggest soldering the CCU yourself by reinforcing the high-current connections. We don't recommend this for residential customers, the board operates at line voltage, the diagnostic to confirm it's a solder issue (versus a different fault) requires an oscilloscope, and a botched repair can cause a fire. We replace the board with new OEM Whirlpool parts and verify the dryer runs full cycles before leaving.</p>

    <h3 class="subhead">Other F-codes you might see</h3>
    <p>Beyond F01, the Whirlpool dryer F-code family includes <strong>F22</strong> (exhaust thermistor fault, $145-$215 sensor replacement), <strong>F23</strong> (heat sensor short), <strong>F24</strong> (inlet thermistor open, same fix as F22), <strong>F26</strong> (motor drive system fault, possible CCU or motor), <strong>F28</strong> (CCU communication fault, usually CCU), <strong>F29</strong> (CCU/MCU communication, usually CCU). Most non-F01 codes still trace back to either the CCU or a sensor on the heating circuit.</p>
  </div>
</section>

