<!-- 05 REPAIR VS REPLACE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05, Repair or replace?</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">When Whirlpool dryer repair makes sense, and when replacement is the honest call.</h2>

    <p class="lead">We give you concrete numbers after diagnostic. Repair cost, replacement cost (comparable model new), and projected remaining service life. Then you decide.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>F01 / CCU failure on a unit under 8 years old:</strong> Repair almost always wins. CCU replacement at $345-$525 is a fraction of a $700-$1,000 replacement dryer, and the rest of the machine (motor, drum, heating element) typically has 5+ years of remaining service life.</li>
      <li><strong>F01 on a 10-plus-year unit:</strong> Case-by-case. If the unit is otherwise in good shape (recent vent service, no other complaints), repair still makes sense. If there are additional complaints (squealing belt, weak element, control panel intermittents), the cumulative repair cost approaches replacement and we'll quote both paths.</li>
      <li><strong>Heating element + thermal fuse + vent service on any age unit:</strong> Almost always repair. This is the bread-and-butter Whirlpool dryer service, $145-$425 depending on which parts are needed, and the dryer comes back to like-new performance.</li>
      <li><strong>Drum belt + idler pulley + drum bearing service on a 12+ year unit:</strong> Tilts toward replacement. When the drum bearing system needs full service ($385-$580 with labor), the rest of the dryer is also at the end of its expected life and other failures will follow within 1-2 years.</li>
      <li><strong>Multiple cumulative failures (F01 + dead heating element + bad door switch):</strong> Replacement usually wins. We've seen customers spend $800+ on stacked repairs over 18 months when replacement at the first failure would have been the better call. We'll tell you honestly when you're in this zone.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

